@mbushong I agree. Trade-offs.
@mbushong In some instances for sure. That‚Äôs why I tweeted that remote vs centralized is a spectrum, not an either/or.
@mbushong Having people in major metropolitan hubs to do meetings instead of flying to all the hubs reduces travel costs.
@mbushong The idea that the entire team should all be in one location strikes me as outdated, given the benefits of distribution.
@mbushong I‚Äôd rather have a distributed team. Easier to meet customers, none of the management of offices, none of the Uber-like HR issues.
There will be many more multi-billion dollar unicorns in the coming decade that are on the ‚Äúremote‚Äù side of the work spectrum.
I don‚Äôt believe remote or centralized is inherently better in the modern era. It‚Äôs simply that remote teams were only made possible recently
‚ÄúCentralized‚Äù teams can often be on the road and thus be collaborating remotely.
Being remote vs. centralized is a spectrum. Some teams are ‚Äúremote‚Äù but have co-working or centralized pockets.
.@pt The trade-offs of remote vs. centralized are management, talent pools, scale, work hours, cost, and HR issues, among many other things.
.@pt I hate that you're spreading this false idea that centralized > remote. It's an old way of thinking, IMHO. It's simply a trade-off.
